ants-terminal (0.7.30-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Session-file integrity. Three ROADMAP § 0.7.12 Tier 2 items
    shipped together as bundle 0.7.30, all in
    sessionmanager.cpp: a SHA-256 envelope around the qCompress
    payload, a pre-flight on qCompress's 4-byte uncompressed-
    length prefix, and per-cell QDataStream::status() checks
    inside the decode loops.
  * Added: V4 SHA-256 envelope around session-file payload
    (SessionManager::serialize, restore, ENVELOPE_MAGIC,
    ENVELOPE_VERSION). Was: session files at
    $XDG_DATA_HOME/ants-terminal/sessions/session_<tabId>.dat were
    raw qCompress output with no payload integrity. Anyone with
    write access to that directory (the user's own UID, a
    compromised local process, an npm dependency, a runaway
    pip install post-exec) could plant a crafted session that fed
    arbitrary codepoints, fg/bg colors, and attribute flags into
    the grid on next restore. Now: serialize wraps the qCompress
    output in a V4 envelope [SHEC magic 0x53484543][envelope
    version=1][SHA-256 of payload (32 bytes)][payload length
    (uint32)][compressed payload]; restore peeks the magic,
    verifies the hash, and refuses to restore on mismatch. Inner
    QDataStream format unchanged (still V3) — the integrity layer
    is framing-only. Legacy V1-V3 files continue to load via the
    magic-peek fall-through; their next save writes them out as
    V4 organically. Locked by tests/features/session_sha256_checksum
    (4 invariants).
  * Added: qUncompress length-prefix pre-flight
    (SessionManager::restore, MAX_UNCOMPRESSED). Was: a crafted
    file claiming 500 MB uncompressed in qCompress's 4-byte big-
    endian prefix triggered a 500 MB allocation that the post-hoc
    raw.size() > 500MB cap could only catch after the damage was
    done. Now: restore reads the first 4 bytes, reconstructs the
    big-endian uint32, and rejects any claim above
    MAX_UNCOMPRESSED (500 MB) BEFORE qUncompress runs — constant-
    time, no allocator pressure. Short-payload guard
    (compressed.size() < 4) keeps the same path safe against
    truncated inputs. Locked by
    tests/features/session_qcompress_length_guard (4 invariants).
  * Changed: QDataStream::status() checks inside cell-decode
    loops (SessionManager::restore readCell / readCombining).
    Was: the readCell lambda was void; a stream truncated mid-
    cell still flowed default-constructed QRgb and uint8_t values
    through QColor::fromRgba etc. into the cell, silently writing
    uninitialized fg/bg/flags into the grid. Now: readCell
    returns bool and short-circuits on
    in.status() != QDataStream::Ok; every call site (scrollback
    cells, screen cells in range, screen cells skipped on width
    or height shrink) is guarded by
    `if (!readCell(...)) return false`. The combining-character
    helper checks status after each codepoint read. Pre-fix, a
    partial save (kernel crash, disk-full mid-write, hostile
    truncation) could materialize as garbage cells in the next
    restore. Locked by tests/features/session_cell_loop_stream_status
    (3 invariants).

