ants-terminal (0.7.27-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * PTY-handler hardening sweep. Two ROADMAP Tier 2 items shipped
    together — child-side FD closure no longer relies on a hard-
    coded fd<1024 cap, and master-side writes no longer drop data
    on EAGAIN.
  * Security: PTY child uses close_range(2) with
    RLIMIT_NOFILE-bounded fallback (Pty::start). Was:
    for (int fd = 3; fd < 1024; ++fd) ::close(fd) — silently leaked
    any inherited FD with index ≥ 1024 into the user's shell on
    systemd-service / container / hardened-server profiles. Qt's
    display socket, D-Bus session connection, plugin HTTP sockets,
    Lua VM eventfds, and the remote-control IPC socket are all
    valid leak candidates. Now: post-fork child branch issues
    ::syscall(SYS_close_range, 3, ~0U, 0) first — single signal-
    safe syscall on Linux 5.9+, atomic over the whole range,
    ignores the soft cap. Fallback path consults
    getrlimit(RLIMIT_NOFILE) and iterates up to the runtime soft
    cap, capped at 65536. Locked by a five-invariant regression
    test (tests/features/pty_closefrom) that flips red against
    pre-fix source.
  * Fixed: Pty::write queues on EAGAIN instead of dropping bytes
    (Pty::write, new Pty::onWriteReady). Was: the master FD is
    non-blocking, so a slow consumer on the slave side could fill
    the kernel PTY buffer; on EAGAIN the write loop broke out with
    the comment "EAGAIN or fatal error", silently dropping the
    unwritten remainder. Provoked by realistic bursts — large
    pastes, AI-dialog command insertions, plugin-driven keystroke
    floods. Now: a new m_pendingWrite byte buffer plus a
    QSocketNotifier(QSocketNotifier::Write) on the master FD
    (initially disabled). On EAGAIN the remainder is queued, the
    notifier enabled; when the kernel signals writability
    onWriteReady drains and disables. Fresh write() calls during
    a non-empty queue append rather than bypass, preserving FIFO
    ordering. Queue capped at 4 MiB so a permanently-stuck slave
    cannot OOM the GUI. Locked by a seven-invariant regression
    test (tests/features/pty_write_eagain_queue) that flips red
    against pre-fix source.

